Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C and boil your #kettle{}. Remove the root and dark green
top from the @leek{1/2}, halve lengthways and slice into thin half moons. Peel and
grate the @garlic{1%clove} (or use a #garlic press{}). Pick the leaves from their
@dried thyme{1/2}(leaves picked) (discard the stalks). Trim the @green beans{80%g}
then chop into thirds.

Pour the boiling @water{400%ml} into a #measuring jug{}. Add the @chicken stock
powder{1} and stir to dissolve. Pop the @British turkey steaks{2} onto a
#plate{} and drizzle on a little @olive oil{1}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}
and sprinkle over half the thyme. Rub the flavourings into the meat, then set aside.

> IMPORTANT! Remember to wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat!

Heat a splash of oil in an #ovenproof dish{} on medium heat, add the leek. Cook
until soft, ~{5-6%minutes}. Add the garlic, green beans, @Arborio rice{175%g} and
remaining thyme. Stir to coat the rice in the oil, then pour in the stock and
bring to the boil. Cover with a tight fitting #lid{} (or foil). Bake on the middle
shelf of your oven for ~{20%minutes}.

Meanwhile, heat a splash of oil in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Pan-fry
the turkey steak until browned, ~{5-6%minutes} on each side.

> IMPORTANT: The turkey is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle!

When cooked, remove the pan from the heat and sprinkle over half the
@grated hard Italian style cheese{80%g}. Leave to rest for ~{1%minute} on a
#board{}.

While the turkey cooks, halve the @premium tomato mix{125%g} and pop into a
#large bowl{}. Season with a good pinch of salt, a drizzle of olive oil and a
small pinch of sugar (if you have some!)

When the risotto has absorbed all of the stock, remove it from the oven and stir
in the @creme fraiche{75%g} and remaining cheese. Taste and season with salt and
pepper, then spoon into #bowls{}. Slice the turkey steak into 1cm thick strips
and place on top. Serve the tomato salad on the side. Enjoy!